summary:
12/29/18 - No weigh in today!
I didnt weigh in today because we had to get up, get ready, and head to my inlaws. But yesterday I...
body:
12/29/18 - No weigh in today!


I didnt weigh in today because we had to get up, get ready, and head to my inlaws. But yesterday I did pretty well (better than this morning which I made the regrettable choice of getting chocolate munchkins) but yeah. The whole day ahead to make better choices, right?


Anywho, today I thought I’d share the app I use to track E V E R Y T H I N G. I used to use Lose It as a calorie counter, but MyFitnessPal is so much more than that. Primarily I like that I have the ability to edit my nutrition goals - it allows me to see my macros, and compare them to the goals I have set for myself! I also just find that I have always had a lot easier time finding the foods I eat and it’s more user friendly. I know tons of people were already using this when I was using Loseit, but I was so attached to Loseit for whatever reason. I finally switched over though about a year and a half ago. I’ll have to make a new YouTube video about it - a lot of people were interested in the one about Loseit!


Well we are about to my inlaws. So that’s it for me today! Have a great weekend. ☺️

summary: Should I hire a PT to learn how to do push-ups & pull-ups in 4-5 months? via /r/Fitness
title: Should I hire a PT to learn how to do push-ups & pull-ups in 4-5 months? via /r/Fitness
body:
I cannot do even one push up or pull up, and I was wondering if I should hire a personal trainer to help me reach a goal of being able to do 25 push-ups & 10 pull-ups within a minimum of 4 months? 4-5 months is what I believe is probably more realistic. I really want to achieve this by March, but where I’m currently at, I’m not so sure.

I currently weigh 97kg and I am 6’5. My body type would be defined as skinny fat.

I joined a gym last month to get into shape and gain strength. The reason isn’t just lifestyle, but a career path I want to follow in which I’m required to be fit & active and reach the goals previously mentioned. I’ve generally always been active, I used to play a lot of sports, but strength wise, I’m very weak. Plus I gained over 12kg over the past year due to medication and bad eating.

I know I have to work on my upper body strength and core to be able to do push-ups and pull-ups, but I’m quite ignorant when it comes to how I should be doing it. I will just look at what machines will workout my upper body and go with that.

My motivation is there, I’ve never been motivated for anything more, I’ve set myself the task of working out 3 times a week minimum, I’ve started using protein supplements, and i’m aiming to shed 7-8kg, but when I randomly try to attempt a push-up or a pull-up, and fail spectacularly, it’s disheartening.

Is it worth having that extra guidance, or is my goal of doing 25 push-ups & 10 pull-ups in 3-5 months achievable on my own?
